<br>
As an enchanter, I rarely charmed anything until I got my level 39 charm, which seems to work quite a bit better than the old one did.<br>
What I usually did when charm-soloing was charm one mob, root a second mob and send the pet at it, debuff and/or DoT the mob I'm fighting.  When charm breaks, second mob should be rooted so you can recharm.  With a debuff and/or DoT on the mob I was fighting, my charmed pet could usually manage to kill two or three mobs in a row.  Then it would be pretty low on health, so I'd break charm and kill it in one DD, or root it and charm another mob to finish the first one off.<br>
The Overthere was a great place for charm soloing (over by the Skyfire exit between 40-42 was gold).<br>
<br>
When duoing with my paladin sweetheart (which I am more often doing), I usually use an animation.  We root the mob and I debuff it, then walk up and let it whack me once (the Berzerker Strength line is my friend, for a free small damage shield), and the animation is doing its damage while Gerbo is fighting as well.  I debuff and DoT, and of course mez all the extra mobs.  Paladin and enchanter make a pretty good duo - once were fighting several blues in Droga and got a train of another bunch from a larger, more powerful group that evac'ed, and we easily lived through it.<br>
We used to play magician/enchantress duo.  It was a little more difficult.  Root was essential to keep the mobs in place, on the pets.  We took down the mobs more quickly due to the magician's good nuking power, but were much more vulnerable, especially when we'd get low on mana.<br>
The druid/enchanter duo has been recommended to me - snare the mob before charming, and it's much safer.  Enchanters also will have Fear to go with the Druids' snare.  Rangers also would benefit from the snare/fear.<br>
<br>
Larger groups are, of course, an enchanter's bread and butter.  It's interesting to try to balance the mana needs of buffing, mezzing and debuffing (slowing is useful in a shaman-less group).  My rule of thumb: if I'm constantly out of mana and the cleric is constantly full, I'm doing too much work and might as well stop debuffing.<br>
<br>
When you attain level 29, find a group and head to Crystal Caverns.  Fight a whooooole bunch of orcs, try to get your group as deep as you can, and you'll really learn the ins and outs of providing good crowd control.  In earlier dungeons than that, you'll find a lot of trains and mez-breakings and won't have many tools to deal with them, so 29+ is good.  In my experience, at least on FV, the upper part with the orcs wasn't a popular place to hunt, so your group might have the place to itself. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.members.shaw.ca/vae/velsig.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
